# Feature Store Standards

This document defines standards for feature engineering, storage, and serving in ML systems.

---

## Feature Definition

### Feature Schema

Every feature must have a documented schema:

| Field | Description | Example |
|-------|-------------|---------|
| name | Unique feature identifier | "user_purchase_count_30d" |
| entity | Primary entity the feature describes | "user", "item", "session" |
| dtype | Data type | float32, int64, string |
| description | What the feature represents | "Number of purchases in last 30 days" |
| owner | Team or person responsible | "team-features" |
| freshness_sla | Maximum staleness allowed | "1 hour" |
| source | Where the raw data comes from | "transactions_table" |

### Feature Naming Convention

```
{entity}_{metric}_{window}_{aggregation}

Examples:
  user_purchase_count_30d
  item_view_rate_7d_avg
  session_duration_total_sum
```

---

## Point-in-Time Correctness

### The Critical Rule

Features must be computed using only data that was available at the time of the prediction. Using future data creates look-ahead bias.

```python
# WRONG: Uses all data up to current time (includes future data at training time)
features = compute_features(df)

# RIGHT: Uses only data available at event_timestamp
features = compute_features(df, as_of=event_timestamp)
```

### Implementation Pattern

```python
def get_features_as_of(entity_id: str, timestamp: datetime) -> dict:
    """Retrieve features as they were at the given timestamp.

    This ensures training uses only data that was available
    at prediction time (no look-ahead bias).
    """
    features = {}
    for feature_def in FEATURE_REGISTRY:
        features[feature_def.name] = feature_def.compute(
            entity_id=entity_id,
            as_of=timestamp,
        )
    return features
```

